  "prompt": "Are there any British airlines that provide cabin crew accommodation?",
  "response": "Yes, many British airlines provide cabin crew accommodation, especially during initial training and when based at an airport away from their home.  Here's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Major Airlines (e.g., British Airways, Virgin Atlantic, easyJet, Jet2.com, TUI Airways):** These airlines almost always provide accommodation during the initial training period. This is because the training is intensive and often requires full-time attendance at a specific location. Beyond initial training, policies vary:\n\n    *   **Base Accommodation:** It's common for cabin crew to be based at an airport. Some airlines will offer initial support, such as a rent subsidy, for crew to find their own accommodation near their base. Others, particularly when bases are in expensive areas, may provide temporary accommodation for newly based crew or for those on short-term contracts.\n    *   **Layover Accommodation:** All major airlines provide hotel accommodation during layovers (when crew have an overnight stay between flights in a different location). This is a legal requirement and part of the standard operating procedure.\n\n*   **Smaller/Regional Airlines:** Similar policies usually apply. Accommodation is generally provided during initial training. Policies on base accommodation are more likely to vary depending on the specific airline and its base locations.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Terms and Conditions:** The availability and terms of cabin crew accommodation (duration, quality, cost contributions, etc.) are always explicitly stated in the employment contract and company policies. It's essential to carefully review these details before accepting a job offer.\n*   **Cost:** While accommodation may be provided, it might not always be free. Some airlines might deduct a small amount from your salary to cover a portion of the accommodation costs.\n*   **Location and Quality:** The quality and location of provided accommodation can vary. During training, it's usually adequate and close to the training center. Layover hotels are generally of a good standard.\n\n**To find the most accurate and up-to-date information:**\n\n1.  **Check the airline's recruitment website:** Job descriptions for cabin crew positions often mention accommodation provisions.\n2.  **Review the employee handbook or company policies:** If you're already employed by the airline, this is the definitive source.\n3.  **Ask during the interview process:** Don't hesitate to ask recruiters about accommodation policies during your interviews.\n\nIn summary, while most British airlines provide accommodation during initial training and layovers, the specifics regarding base accommodation should be verified directly with the airline during the recruitment process.",
